**Tools class — `WeatherTools.cs`**

```csharp
using ModelContextProtocol.Server;
using System.ComponentModel;
using System.Text.Json;

[McpServerToolType]
public class WeatherTools(HttpClient httpClient, ILogger<WeatherTools> logger)
{
    [McpServerTool, Description("Get current weather for a city.")]
    public async Task<string> GetWeather(
        [Description("City name, e.g. 'London'")] string city,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        logger.LogInformation("Fetching weather for {City}", city);
        var response = await httpClient.GetStringAsync(
            $"/v1/current.json?q={Uri.EscapeDataString(city)}", cancellationToken);
        return response;
    }

    [McpServerTool, Description("Get multi-day weather forecast for a city.")]
    public async Task<string> GetForecast(
        [Description("City name")] string city,
        [Description("Number of forecast days (1-7)")] int days,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        logger.LogInformation("Fetching {Days}-day forecast for {City}", days, city);
        var response = await httpClient.GetStringAsync(
            $"/v1/forecast.json?q={Uri.EscapeDataString(city)}&days={days}", cancellationToken);
        return response;
    }
}
```

**`Program.cs` — stdio transport**

```csharp
using Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;

var builder = Host.CreateApplicationBuilder(args);

// CRITICAL: log to stderr only — stdout is reserved for JSON-RPC
builder.Logging.AddConsole(options =>
    options.LogToStandardErrorThreshold = LogLevel.Trace);

builder.Services.AddHttpClient<WeatherTools>(client =>
{
    client.BaseAddress = new Uri("https://api.weatherapi.com");
});

builder.Services.AddMcpServer()
    .WithStdioServerTransport()
    .WithToolsFromAssembly();

await builder.Build().RunAsync();
```

---

### How DI works for MCP tools

The SDK has two injection styles:

| Style | Class type | How services arrive |
|-------|-----------|-------------------|
| **Constructor injection** | Non-static class | Services injected via primary constructor (shown above). Class is resolved from DI per invocation. |
| **Method parameter injection** | Static class | DI services appear as method parameters alongside tool params. |

**Key rule:** The SDK automatically distinguishes tool parameters from injected services. Types registered in DI (`HttpClient`, `ILogger<T>`, `IMcpServer`, `CancellationToken`, `IProgress<>`) are **injected silently** — they never appear in the tool's JSON schema that the LLM sees. Only parameters with `[Description]` are exposed to the LLM.

So in `GetWeather` above, the LLM sees only `city` (a string). `HttpClient`, `ILogger`, and `CancellationToken` are resolved automatically at call time.

**Constructor injection** (non-static, shown above) is preferred when tools share services or state. **Method injection** (static class) works for simpler, stateless tools.
